    <h3 style="color: white; margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 1rem;">Educational Deep Dive: Vector vs. Raster: Why PDF is Different</h3>
    <p style="color: rgba(255,255,255,0.8); line-height: 1.6; margin-bottom: 1rem;">
        To extract the best quality from your files, you need to understand <strong>Vector</strong> vs. <strong>Raster</strong>. JPGs and PNGs are raster, meaning they are built from a fixed grid of pixels. If you zoom in too much, they get blurry and "pixelated."
    </p>
    <p style="color: rgba(255,255,255,0.8); line-height: 1.6; margin-bottom: 1rem;">
        Many PDFs, however, contain vector data—mathematical paths that define shapes and text. This is why you can zoom into a bank statement or a digital blueprint and the text stays perfectly sharp. When you use the Webtigo converter, we transform those mathematical vectors into high-resolution pixels, giving you an image that captures every detail of the original document.
    </p>

